For a long period of time, the virtually unregulated advertising industry used aggressively widespread marketing strategies that caused a great deal of confusion and annoyance with consumers, while simultaneously obstructing legitimate television and radio programs. Advertisement Segregation Act of 1968, in short, instituted print and broadcast standards that would ensure reasonable media-consumer relations along with measures to establish greater accountability for advertising providers.

Such standards and regulations have resulted in bans on outdoor audio ads, heavily restricted leaflet distribution, and broadcast advertising being restricted to the times between regularly scheduled programming.

Man, this is pretty extreme, but given how out of hand things became, it seems very reasonable.
